ing ludic elements challenges the traditional view of drama as principally mimesis, or imitation, revealing stageplays to be improvisational experiments and participatory explorations into the motive, means, and value of recreation. Delving into both canonical masterpieces and hidden gems, this innovative volume stakes a claim for play as the crucial link between games and early modern theatre, and for the early modern theatre as a critical site for unraveling the continued cultural significance and performative efficacy of gameplay today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aGames in art. 0aGamesxHistory. 0aPerforming arts. 4aCultural Studies. 4aCultural studies. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aFestivals, Theatre, and Performance. 4aGame Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aLiterary studies: c 1400 to c 1600. 4aLiterary studies: plays and playwrights. 4aShakespeare. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aDrama, theatre, play, games, early modern.1 aBadir, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBishop, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBishop, Tom, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBloom, Gina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloom, Gina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBushnell, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeSouza-Coelho, Shawn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenberg, Marissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirschfeld, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKathman, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKorda, Natasha, e